  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>Scotsman — Ali Group's flagship ice specialist in LA</h2>
      <p>
        Scotsman has been under Ali Group ownership since 2012, out of Vernon Hills, Illinois. Since the July 2022
        Ali Group acquisition of Welbilt ($3.5 billion), the Ali ice family now spans four of the biggest US
        commercial ice brands: Manitowoc (the #1 US installed base), Scotsman (the #2, and widely preferred for
        cocktail-grade ice quality), Ice-O-Matic (the undercounter specialist), and Kold-Draft (the luxury
        1-1/4-inch craft-cocktail cube). For a multi-unit LA operator running Scotsman plus Manitowoc plus
        Ice-O-Matic across a restaurant group, that's useful: a single service partner can cover the whole
        family through overlapping parts distribution.
      </p>
      <p>
        What distinguishes Scotsman in LA service is the Brilliance and Aquasphere lines — the Gourmet clear
        cube and the 1.5-inch sphere ice formats. These aren't ice-as-utility; they're ice-as-signature. The
        Brilliance Gourmet cube is the default behind-the-bar spec in LA's craft cocktail scene — The Varnish,
        Seven Grand, Thunderbolt, the top cocktail programs at the five-star hotels. Aquasphere is the premium
        format above that, when the cocktail program wants the single spherical ice ball photographed in the
        glass. Both require specific service knowledge, not generic ice-machine techniques.
      </p>
      <p>
        On the broader Scotsman commercial lineup — Prodigy Plus cubers, Meridian nugget, HID dispensers — the
        service work is more familiar. Ice machine repair across Los Angeles on Scotsman follows the same patterns
        as Manitowoc: LA hard-water scale, urban condenser fouling, and the specific Prodigy Plus diagnostic
        flow on the front-panel display. We run these calls weekly across LA County.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2>What we fix on Scotsman ice machines</h2>
      <p class="intro">
        Common Scotsman failures, in rough frequency order across LA commercial service calls:
      </p>
      <div class="code-grid">
        <div class="code-card">
          <h3>Prodigy Plus diagnostic codes</h3>
          <p>Prodigy Plus runs a microprocessor control with front-panel LED status and service-port diagnostic
          output. Long freeze, long harvest, water level faults, temperature sensor out-of-range — we read the
          status flow and work down the list before condemning parts.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-card">
          <h3>LA hard-water scale service</h3>
          <p>#1 recurring Scotsman issue in LA. Calcium films on the evaporator plate and water distribution tube
          cause harvest time drift, cube-clarity degradation (especially on Brilliance Gourmet), and eventually
          probe failures. Full descale protocol every 3–6 months in high-volume operations.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-card">
          <h3>Water inlet valve</h3>
          <p>Calcium buildup on the plunger, valve won't seat, water drip into trough, or slow fill causing long
          freeze events. Standard stocked part.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-card">
          <h3>Water curtain / thermistor bin control</h3>
          <p>Hinge pin corrosion, sticky curtain, failed bin-full thermistor. Scotsman's bin-full detection uses
          ice-contact thermistor rather than the mechanical switch on some competitors — different failure mode,
          different diagnostic.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-card">
          <h3>Ice thickness sensor</h3>
          <p>Probe fouling or drift, premature or delayed harvest trigger. Scotsman ITP failures show up as
          ice-too-thin or ice-too-thick symptoms before they show as error codes. Field-replaceable.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-card">
          <h3>Condenser fouling</h3>
          <p>Quarterly cleaning is factory spec; in urban LA with kitchen exhaust nearby, bi-monthly is more
          realistic. E04-equivalent high-condenser-temp faults almost always trace to coil loading.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-card">
          <h3>Harvest solenoid</h3>
          <p>Hot gas valve redirecting refrigerant to thaw ice off the evaporator. Stuck closed: no harvest.
          Leaking open: slow freeze. Common stocked part for Prodigy Plus line.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-card">
          <h3>Meridian MXG auger + gearbox</h3>
          <p>Nugget-line-specific. Auger motor amperage creeping up under load signals a rebuild. Gearbox bearing
          grind is audible. Extrusion-chamber wear affects nugget texture. We service the whole assembly as
          a system.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-card">
          <h3>Brilliance / Aquasphere evaporator service</h3>
          <p>The specialty-cube architectures have distinct evaporator geometries — not the standard cube plate.
          Service work requires familiarity with the specific cocktail-grade cube or sphere release dynamics.
          Not every generic ice tech handles these.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2>Scotsman model map by line</h2>
      <p class="intro">The Scotsman lineup LA kitchens actually run:</p>
